column24: I certainly have learned things and am glad to have participated. It was particularly nice to interact with the librarians. However, I feel it might have been better to either have larger cohorts or discipline-specific cohorts or even no cohorts at all. I like the idea of being in a cohort, but maybe that should have been done after people saw who was active and who wasn't. After the first day or two, nobody really participated much, and then the participation that did happen was spread out over several different channels. If there was just one channel we could all meet and discuss things in threads, which would make it more lively.

column24: I thought GSRI was incredibly helpful, and really well organized. There was so much content covered over just the course of a week, and a ton of resources for connecting with both UW Library staff and databases. I also really liked that you could go throughout the course at your own pace. To be totally transparent, I'm in the process of wrapping up a job on the east coast, so I wasn't able to engage as much as I would have liked. I will definitely be taking the time to review a number of these resources prior to my orientation to the COPHP program on Sept 29th, when I have a little more time to sit down and go through all of this in-depth.

column21: While all five modules in this course were useful, Modules 2 and 4 were the most beneficial for me. Further, better learning how to navigate and use the research subject guide for my subject was, without doubt, quite helpful. Learning how to set up Husky OnNet was also quite beneficial. In addition, I appreciated the links and discussion associated with data management.
column22: The most useful part of GSRI, for me, was certainly learning about new ways of following citation trails that I was previously not aware of.
column23: It would have been nice if scholarly publishing was included as a larger component of Module 5: "Taking your Research to the Next Level." At present, this is only primarily discussed within activity option #2 of Module 5. The implications of the publication process, signing a publication contract, and more could be considered further in this module. On another note, the last two sentences in the first paragraph on Citation Managers in Module 3 repeat each other: "Citation managers save you valuable time and energy by automatically capturing citations, generating bibliographies, and organizing a custom library of sources for you. A citation manager saves you valuable time and energy by automatically capturing citations, generating bibliographies, and organizing a custom library of sources for you." This is just a small typo. Also, it would be nice if RSS is defined earlier on the â€œAlerts and Notifications" page in Module 3.
column24: This course was both well-organized and filled with a wealth of invaluable information; the topics were broken up well. Further, the two synchronous sessions as well as the ability to ask questions and discuss module topics in Slack with mentors made the GSRI all the more meaningful, helpful, and personable.

column24: As a younger grad student, there was a decent chunk of the information presented that was a part of my undergrad and even high school education. For example, citation managers and database search methods (like Boolean commands) were commonplace in my classes. I did find, after asking some of my older cohorts, that this information was super beneficial to them as they did not grow up with this technology. Regardless of tech proficiency, I did think that it was valuable to connect directly with librarians and other grad students all working toward the same goal of research and making academia a more accessible, productive place. Moreover, having all of these resources in one place gave me a much better idea of what I still have to learn and how I can go about improving my research skills.
